COLOMBO , February 11 -LRB- Xinhua -RRB- -- Norwegian Foreign Minister Knut Vollebaek will visit Sri Lanka next Wednesday in a bid to broker peace in the war-torn island nation , the state radio said Friday .
Minister Vollebaek will hold talks with Sri Lankan President Chandrika Kumaratunga , his counterpart Lakshman Kadirgamar and opposition leader Ranil Wickremesinghe as well as other political figures , the radio said in its night broadcast .
Vollebaek was previously scheduled to visit Sri Lanka on January 15 to examine prospects for peace , but the trip was cancelled as Sri Lankan Foreign Minister Kadirgamar was not in the country .
In late January , a Norwegian delegation led by State Secretary Leiv Lunde arrived in Colombo to prepare the ground for active revival of the talks between the government and Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam -LRB- LTTE -RRB- rebels who have been fighting a 17-year -old war for a separate Tamil state in Sri Lanka 's north and east .
The delegation met top Sri Lankan government officials and leaders of the main opposition and some smaller Tamil political parties .
President Kumaratunga revealed in an interview after her reelection as president last December that Norway was trying to help end the conflict which has plagued Sri Lanka since 1983 .
Norway began its efforts to revive its role in arranging peace talks after Kumaratunga said in the interview that she was ready for Norwegian facilitation .
